<p><i>This article is about writer <strong class="selflink">Robert E. Howard</strong>. For the Medal of Honor recipient, try <a href="/wiki/Robert_L._Howard" title="Robert L. Howard">Robert L. Howard</a>.</i></p>
<p><b>Robert Ervin Howard</b> (January 22, 1906 – June 11, 1936)<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> was an <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">American</a> <a href="/wiki/Author" title="Author">author</a> who wrote <a href="/wiki/Pulp_fiction" title="Pulp fiction">pulp fiction</a> in a diverse range of genres.</p>
<p>He created — in the pages of the <a href="/wiki/Great_Depression" title="Great Depression">Depression</a>-era <a href="/wiki/Pulp_magazine" title="Pulp magazine">pulp magazine</a> <i><a href="/wiki/Weird_Tales" title="Weird Tales">Weird Tales</a></i> — Conan the Cimmerian, a.k.a. <a href="/wiki/Conan_the_Barbarian" title="Conan the Barbarian">Conan the Barbarian</a>, a character whose pop-culture imprint might be compared to such icons as <a href="/wiki/Tarzan" title="Tarzan">Tarzan of the Apes</a>, <a href="/wiki/Count_Dracula" title="Count Dracula">Count Dracula</a>, <a href="/wiki/Sherlock_Holmes" title="Sherlock Holmes">Sherlock Holmes</a>, and <a href="/wiki/James_Bond" title="James Bond">James Bond</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>With Conan and his other heroes Howard created the genre now known as <a href="/wiki/Sword_and_sorcery" title="Sword and sorcery">sword-and-sorcery</a> in the late 1920s and early 1930s,<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2" title=""><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3" title=""><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup> spawning a wide swath of imitators<sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4" title=""><span>[</span>5<span>]</span></a></sup> and giving him an influence in the fantasy field rivaled only by <a href="/wiki/J.R.R._Tolkien" title="J.R.R. Tolkien" class="mw-redirect">J.R.R. Tolkien</a> and Tolkien's similarly inspired creation of the modern genre of <a href="/wiki/High_Fantasy" title="High Fantasy" class="mw-redirect">High Fantasy</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5" title=""><span>[</span>6<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Howard remains a highly read author,<sup id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6" title=""><span>[</span>7<span>]</span></a></sup> with his best work endlessly reprinted.<sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7" title=""><span>[</span>8<span>]</span></a></sup> He has been compared to other American masters of the weird, gloomy, and spectral, such as <a href="/wiki/Nathaniel_Hawthorne" title="Nathaniel Hawthorne">Nathaniel Hawthorne</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-8" title=""><span>[</span>9<span>]</span></a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Herman_Melville" title="Herman Melville">Herman Melville</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9" title=""><span>[</span>10<span>]</span></a></sup> and <a href="/wiki/Jack_London" title="Jack London">Jack London</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-10" title=""><span>[</span>11<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
